  <!-- What is Salary Sacrifice? -->
  <section class="border-t border-hairline bg-canvas-soft py-16">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 sm:px-6">
      <h2 class="mb-8 text-center text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-ink" style="letter-spacing: -0.02em;">
        What is Salary Sacrifice for Pensions?
      </h2>

      <div class="prose prose-gray max-w-none text-body">
        <p class="mb-4">
          <strong>Salary sacrifice</strong> (also called "salary exchange" or "SMART pension") is a tax-efficient arrangement where you agree to give up a portion of your gross salary in exchange for an equivalent pension contribution from your employer. Because the sacrificed amount is never treated as your income, you pay <strong>no income tax and no employee National Insurance</strong> on it. Your employer also saves 15% employer NI, which some employers pass into your pension as an additional contribution.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4">
          In contrast, a <strong>standard "relief at source" pension</strong> takes your contribution from your net pay, with the government adding basic rate tax relief (20%) automatically. Higher rate taxpayers must claim additional relief via self-assessment. Crucially, standard contributions do <strong>not</strong> save employee or employer National Insurance.
        </p>

        <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">The Salary Sacrifice Formula</h3>
        <div class="rounded-lg bg-canvas-soft-2 p-4 font-mono text-sm text-ink">
          Net Cost to You = Sacrificed Amount × (1 − Income Tax Rate − Employee NI Rate)
        </div>

        <p class="mb-4 mt-4">
          For a <strong>basic rate taxpayer</strong> (20% tax, 8% NI): Net cost = Sacrificed Amount × 0.72. Sacrificing £1,000 costs just £720 in take-home pay.<br />
          For a <strong>higher rate taxpayer</strong> (40% tax, 2% NI): Net cost = Sacrificed Amount × 0.58. Sacrificing £1,000 costs just £580.<br />
          For an <strong>additional rate taxpayer</strong> (45% tax, 2% NI): Net cost = Sacrificed Amount × 0.53. Sacrificing £1,000 costs just £530.
        </p>

        <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Standard vs Salary Sacrifice Comparison</h3>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-hairline">
          <table class="w-full text-left text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline bg-canvas-soft-2">
                <th class="p-3 font-medium text-ink">Feature</th>
                <th class="p-3 font-medium text-ink">Standard Pension</th>
                <th class="p-3 font-medium text-ink">Salary Sacrifice</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-xs tabular-nums">
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline/50">
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">Gross contribution</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">£2,500</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">£2,500</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline/50">
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">Income tax saved</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">£500 (20%)</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-success-deep">£500 (20%)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline/50">
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">Employee NI saved</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">£0</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-success-deep">£200 (8%)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline/50">
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">Employer NI saved</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">£0</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-success-deep">£375 (15%)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline/50">
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">Net cost to you</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">£1,800</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-success-deep">£1,800</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-hairline/50">
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">Total in pension</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-body font-sans">£2,500</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-success-deep">£2,500</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="bg-success/5">
                <td class="p-3 font-sans font-semibold text-ink">With employer NI pass-on</td>
                <td class="p-3 font-sans text-body">£2,500</td>
                <td class="p-3 font-semibold text-success-deep">£2,875</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mb-3 mt-8 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Who Should Consider Salary Sacrifice?</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
            <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Higher &amp; Additional Rate Taxpayers</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-body">Salary sacrifice saves 42% (higher rate) or 47% (additional rate) in combined tax and NI. The savings are substantial and compound significantly over time. Higher rate relief is automatic — no self-assessment claim needed.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
            <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Employees Near the £100k Personal Allowance Threshold</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-body">Salary sacrifice reduces your gross salary, helping you stay below the £100,000 Personal Allowance taper threshold. This preserves your full £12,570 tax-free allowance — worth up to £5,000 per year in tax savings.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
            <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Parents Affected by HICBC</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-body">If your Adjusted Net Income is between £60,000 and £80,000, salary sacrifice can reduce your income below the High Income Child Benefit Charge threshold, helping you retain some or all of your Child Benefit payments.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4">
            <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Basic Rate Taxpayers with Employer NI Pass-On</h4>
            <p class="text-sm text-body">Even basic rate taxpayers benefit from the 8% employee NI saving. If your employer passes on the 15% NI saving, your pension gets an extra boost — turning a £2,500 contribution into £2,875 for the same net cost.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mb-3 mt-8 text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Salary Sacrifice Pros and Cons</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-success/30 bg-success/5 p-4">
            <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-success-deep">Advantages</h4>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-body">
              <li>• Saves employee NI (8% or 2%) that standard pensions cannot</li>
              <li>• Employer saves 15% NI — may be passed into your pension</li>
              <li>• Higher rate relief is automatic — no self-assessment claim needed</li>
              <li>• Reduces gross salary, helping preserve Personal Allowance</li>
              <li>• Can reduce HICBC and student loan repayments</li>
              <li>• Simple payroll integration with no tax relief paperwork</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-error/30 bg-error/5 p-4">
            <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-error">Trade-offs</h4>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-body">
              <li>• Requires employer participation — not all employers offer it</li>
              <li>• Cannot reduce pay below National Minimum Wage</li>
              <li>• May reduce mortgage borrowing capacity</li>
              <li>• Can affect means-tested benefits and tax credits</li>
              <li>• Contractual change — not easy to opt out month-to-month</li>
              <li>• Reduces gross salary for employer pension scheme reference</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

